    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Addressing Silent Cancers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Seana Shaw letter warns that silent cancers (gastric, ovarian, colon, lung) msut be addressed in more pro-active fashion (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gastric and esophageal cancer are silent cancers that are usually detected after they have spread (''Beyond the Pain of Gastric Reflux,'' Aug. 15). Routine screening with endoscopy, in an effort to detect the conditions in an early stage, will add much additional information regarding associated factors.</p>
        <p>Silent cancers (gastric, ovarian, colon, lung) have to be addressed in a more proactive fashion in our country. Other countries are more rigorous in their attempts at early detection.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gastric and esophageal cancer are silent cancers that are usually detected after they have spread (''Beyond the Pain of Gastric Reflux,'' Aug. 15). Routine screening with endoscopy, in an effort to detect the conditions in an early stage, will add much additional information regarding associated factors.</p>
        <p>Silent cancers (gastric, ovarian, colon, lung) have to be addressed in a more proactive fashion in our country. Other countries are more rigorous in their attempts at early detection.</p>
        <p>On a personal note, I was recently told I had gastric cancer. Although this cancer is considered rare in women, that may no longer be the case.</p>
        <p>DR. SEANA SHAW  Miami Beach</p>
      </block>
